00:01:08.760 --> 00:01:09.320
MICHAEL AMES: Two?

00:01:09.320 --> 00:01:09.650
MICHAEL SHORT: Yeah.

00:01:09.650 --> 00:01:10.000
Well--

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:10.610
MICHAEL AMES: --your bananas.

00:01:10.610 --> 00:01:12.290
MICHAEL SHORT: The
bananas and the thing

00:01:12.290 --> 00:01:13.540
that we dreamed up today, so--

00:01:13.540 --> 00:01:14.665
MICHAEL AMES: This morning?

00:01:14.665 --> 00:01:15.270
OK.

00:01:15.270 --> 00:01:16.580
So you want an intro those--

00:01:16.580 --> 00:01:17.030
MICHAEL SHORT: Sure.

00:01:17.030 --> 00:01:18.680
MICHAEL AMES: --and
I'll, I don't know--

00:01:18.680 --> 00:01:19.820
MICHAEL SHORT: Fill
in what I get wrong.

00:01:19.820 --> 00:01:21.362
Also, Mike's going
to talk about what

00:01:21.362 --> 00:01:23.780
we're going to do together,
which is called NAA,

00:01:23.780 --> 00:01:25.940
or Nuclear Activation Analysis.

00:01:25.940 --> 00:01:28.370
There are many, many
ways of measuring

00:01:28.370 --> 00:01:30.500
what sort of impurities
may exist in materials,

00:01:30.500 --> 00:01:32.450
and this is among
the most sensitive.

00:01:32.450 --> 00:01:34.903
We happen to have
a nuclear reactor.

00:01:34.903 --> 00:01:36.320
So what we will
be doing, what I'm

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:38.892
going to ask each of you guys
to do for a special assignment

00:01:38.892 --> 00:01:41.350
that not graded, except you'll
need it for the problem set,

00:01:41.350 --> 00:01:44.180
so it kind of is, is
I want each of you

00:01:44.180 --> 00:01:47.810
to bring something into me
that weighs about 50 milligrams

00:01:47.810 --> 00:01:51.110
in one piece, fits in
here, is not fissionable--

00:01:51.110 --> 00:01:54.185
so if you have uranium at home,
I shouldn't know about it.

00:01:54.185 --> 00:01:56.060
And we also ask that
you don't bring anything

00:01:56.060 --> 00:01:59.750
in that is too salty, because
sodium activates like crazy.

00:01:59.750 --> 00:02:02.360
And each of you, using your
knowledge of radioactive decay

00:02:02.360 --> 00:02:05.060
that we learned Tuesday
and today, and the Bateman

00:02:05.060 --> 00:02:08.120
equations in serious
radioactive decay next Tuesday

00:02:08.120 --> 00:02:10.610
and Thursday are going to
calculate what impurities

00:02:10.610 --> 00:02:12.540
exist in your sample.

00:02:12.540 --> 00:02:13.730
What is your sample?

00:02:13.730 --> 00:02:14.560
It's--

00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:15.085
MICHAEL AMES: You're
not going to be

00:02:15.085 --> 00:02:16.080
able to do the calculations.

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:17.630
MICHAEL SHORT: We're going
to make some estimates of--

00:02:17.630 --> 00:02:18.140
MICHAEL AMES: Oh, OK.

00:02:18.140 --> 00:02:20.265
MICHAEL SHORT: The isotopes
that you'll let us see.

00:02:20.265 --> 00:02:22.340
The shorts, yeah.

00:02:22.340 --> 00:02:24.507
I know we're not going to
get every impurity, right?

00:02:24.507 --> 00:02:26.298
MICHAEL AMES: Well,
we're not going to able

00:02:26.298 --> 00:02:27.478
to run it next week.

00:02:27.478 --> 00:02:30.020
MICHAEL SHORT: Yes, but I will
want your materials next week.

00:02:30.020 --> 00:02:31.190
OK.

00:02:31.190 --> 00:02:32.810
So by Tuesday, I'd
like each of you

00:02:32.810 --> 00:02:35.240
to come bring something
in for what you'd

00:02:35.240 --> 00:02:38.750
like to know the elemental
composition consisting

00:02:38.750 --> 00:02:40.880
of the following elements.

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:42.470
Let's see.

00:02:42.470 --> 00:02:46.310
Problem sets, I think
I've got it right up here.

00:02:46.310 --> 00:02:49.210
Let me just clone the screen.

00:02:49.210 --> 00:02:50.710
So you can see what
we can look for.

00:02:50.710 --> 00:02:52.823
So this is provided
to me by Mike.

00:02:52.823 --> 00:02:55.240
We're going to do what's called
a short nuclear activation

00:02:55.240 --> 00:02:59.640
analysis run looking for any of
the elements up on this list.

00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:03.040
Shorts 1 with extremely short
half-lives, and shorts 2

00:03:03.040 --> 00:03:05.560
with elements in the
half-lives of hours.

00:03:05.560 --> 00:03:08.810
And Mike, I had a question
for you now that we're live.

00:03:08.810 --> 00:03:10.570
Can we count arsenic
in that list?

00:03:10.570 --> 00:03:13.045
Because it's
24-point-something hours.

00:03:13.045 --> 00:03:14.980
MICHAEL AMES: Yeah,
we could do arsenic.

00:03:14.980 --> 00:03:15.730
MICHAEL SHORT: OK.

00:03:15.730 --> 00:03:19.608
MICHAEL AMES: It's not
a great shorts element.

00:03:19.608 --> 00:03:21.150
You'd probably have
to have something

00:03:21.150 --> 00:03:22.710
with a bunch of arsenic in it.

00:03:22.710 --> 00:03:24.210
MICHAEL SHORT: So
if any of you guys

00:03:24.210 --> 00:03:26.010
have some food that
you bought online

00:03:26.010 --> 00:03:28.020
and you don't know what sort
of contaminants there are,

00:03:28.020 --> 00:03:29.812
or if you've got a
piece of your fingernail

00:03:29.812 --> 00:03:32.850
and want to see if you
are what you eat, or--

00:03:32.850 --> 00:03:34.980
MICHAEL AMES: After
telling you why fingernails

00:03:34.980 --> 00:03:38.670
would be a great
sample, we might

00:03:38.670 --> 00:03:42.720
run afoul of the human
subjects in research issue

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:43.435
with fingernails.

00:03:43.435 --> 00:03:45.185
MICHAEL SHORT: What
about dog fingernails?

00:03:45.185 --> 00:03:46.295
MICHAEL AMES:
--believe it or don't.

00:03:46.295 --> 00:03:47.837
Ah, yes, your dogs
are probably not--

00:03:47.837 --> 00:03:48.630
MICHAEL SHORT: OK.

00:03:48.630 --> 00:03:50.370
So clip your pets'
claws if you want

00:03:50.370 --> 00:03:52.260
to see if they
are what they eat,

00:03:52.260 --> 00:03:57.720
or don't tell me what nail the
thing came from, or get a--

00:03:57.720 --> 00:04:00.450
slice up a piece of a peanut or
whatever your favorite food is.

00:04:00.450 --> 00:04:02.980
Or if you want to see if
there are any metal dyes used

00:04:02.980 --> 00:04:05.285
in your clothing, cut out a
little 50 milligram square,

00:04:05.285 --> 00:04:07.410
it'll be like a fashion
statement and an experiment

00:04:07.410 --> 00:04:09.390
at the same time, right?

00:04:09.390 --> 00:04:11.110
So we ask that it's
about 50 milligrams,

00:04:11.110 --> 00:04:14.490
it's gotta fit in here, it's
gotta be not that salty and not

00:04:14.490 --> 00:04:18.899
fissionable, and we're going to
pack a couple of these in one

00:04:18.899 --> 00:04:20.940
of these rabbits, these
polyethylene rabbits.

00:04:20.940 --> 00:04:23.340
We call it those, one,
because everything in nuclear

00:04:23.340 --> 00:04:26.137
is named after animals and farm
implements for some reason.

00:04:26.137 --> 00:04:28.470
Did I go over that with you
guys the first day of class?

00:04:28.470 --> 00:04:31.690
Barns, shakes, pigs, rabbits?

00:04:31.690 --> 00:04:32.190
OK.

00:04:32.190 --> 00:04:35.720
So a rabbit is a little capsule.

00:04:35.720 --> 00:04:37.830
Do you pop open or
you screw it open?

00:04:37.830 --> 00:04:40.075
Oh yeah, there's like a
square nut at the top.

00:04:40.075 --> 00:04:42.450
Just a little capsule that
goes through a pneumatic tube,

00:04:42.450 --> 00:04:44.580
kind of like the
old bank machines,

00:04:44.580 --> 00:04:47.520
and it'll go firing into the
reactor, sit there for a while,

00:04:47.520 --> 00:04:49.590
and get pneumatically
sucked back out so that we

00:04:49.590 --> 00:04:53.680
can calculate the activation and
decay of the isotopes within.

00:04:53.680 --> 00:04:56.070
And a pig is just a
big heavy thing of lead

00:04:56.070 --> 00:04:58.240
where you keep pieces
of things that you

00:04:58.240 --> 00:04:59.880
irradiated for shielding.

00:04:59.880 --> 00:05:02.430
So if you notice the sort
of methodology theme here,

00:05:02.430 --> 00:05:05.700
farms, pigs, rabbits,
barns, shakes.

00:05:05.700 --> 00:05:08.370
Anyone else you know any
other farmy nuclear units?

