00:14:05.660 --> 00:14:08.480
So an electron capture,
another way of,

00:14:08.480 --> 00:14:12.140
well, destroying positive
charge would be for the nucleus

00:14:12.140 --> 00:14:13.520
to capture an electron.

00:14:13.520 --> 00:14:15.620
So either it can
emit a positron,

00:14:15.620 --> 00:14:17.600
giving away some
positive charge,

00:14:17.600 --> 00:14:20.243
or it can capture an
electron, destroying

00:14:20.243 --> 00:14:21.410
one of the positive charges.

00:14:21.410 --> 00:14:25.160
And in each case here, we've got
a proton that becomes a neutron

00:14:25.160 --> 00:14:26.090
and something.

00:14:26.090 --> 00:14:29.210
I'm won't be specific as to
which one because positron

00:14:29.210 --> 00:14:32.600
and electron capture, well,
two different but similar kind

00:14:32.600 --> 00:14:34.100
of decaying mechanisms.

00:14:34.100 --> 00:14:36.740
And then what you
get is this hole

00:14:36.740 --> 00:14:38.910
where the electron used to be.

00:14:38.910 --> 00:14:40.670
And that's not a very
stable configuration

00:14:40.670 --> 00:14:44.390
for an atom to have, let's say,
one fewer electron then protons

00:14:44.390 --> 00:14:46.730
and especially to have a
hole in the inner shell.

00:14:46.730 --> 00:14:49.490
So you get this cascade from
straight-up from high school

00:14:49.490 --> 00:14:53.330
chemistry of electrons falling
from one shell to the next

00:14:53.330 --> 00:14:55.730
and giving off
characteristic X-rays--

00:14:55.730 --> 00:14:57.650
that's me that cross
that out there--

00:14:57.650 --> 00:14:59.240
because you will
find misinformation

00:14:59.240 --> 00:15:01.430
all over the place
online, and someone

00:15:01.430 --> 00:15:03.980
might make a great
figure and mislabel

00:15:03.980 --> 00:15:07.040
an electron-emitted photon
as a gamma ray, and remember,

00:15:07.040 --> 00:15:09.320
we said gammas come
from the nucleus,

00:15:09.320 --> 00:15:12.098
otherwise they're
indistinguishable photons.

00:15:12.098 --> 00:15:13.640
And so in electron
capture, you don't

00:15:13.640 --> 00:15:16.347
need much of an
energy difference

00:15:16.347 --> 00:15:17.930
between the parents
and the daughters,

00:15:17.930 --> 00:15:23.090
unlike positron decay where
for positron decay to happen,

00:15:23.090 --> 00:15:25.550
you have to have
Q at least equal

00:15:25.550 --> 00:15:31.660
to 1.022 MeV, which is the
same as 2 times the rest

00:15:31.660 --> 00:15:34.220
mass of the electron.

00:15:34.220 --> 00:15:36.850
For electron capture, you don't.

00:15:36.850 --> 00:15:39.220
This can happen at
just about any energy.

00:15:39.220 --> 00:15:41.350
As long as you can overcome
just the binding energy

00:15:41.350 --> 00:15:43.450
of the electron,
which is negligible

00:15:43.450 --> 00:15:46.090
compared to these sort
of nuclear energy levels.

00:15:46.090 --> 00:15:48.110
And so this is the Q equation.

00:15:48.110 --> 00:15:51.820
Keep in mind, these deltas
here are excess masses.

00:15:51.820 --> 00:15:54.310
So I'll put this up
again, the excess mass

00:15:54.310 --> 00:15:58.270
is the real mass minus
the terrible approximation

00:15:58.270 --> 00:16:00.220
of a nucleide's mass.

00:16:00.220 --> 00:16:03.610
And this way, excess mass and
real mass are directly related,

00:16:03.610 --> 00:16:06.340
so you could plug
in masses here,

00:16:06.340 --> 00:16:07.900
you could plug in
binding energies

00:16:07.900 --> 00:16:12.040
by making everything with
a minus sign, and so on.

00:16:12.040 --> 00:16:14.950
I think I've repeated myself
enough for the Q equation

00:16:14.950 --> 00:16:16.860
stuff, would you guys agree?

00:16:16.860 --> 00:16:19.590
Yeah, OK.

00:16:19.590 --> 00:16:21.980
And so these are actually
two competing mechanisms.

00:16:21.980 --> 00:16:24.710
So shown here is the
decay of sodium-22

00:16:24.710 --> 00:16:28.340
which we don't want to happen in
our nuclear activation analysis

00:16:28.340 --> 00:16:30.320
because it gets pretty toasty.

00:16:30.320 --> 00:16:32.300
It can either proceed--

00:16:32.300 --> 00:16:34.430
there's a kind of hidden
part of the diagram

00:16:34.430 --> 00:16:36.710
that I drew in to make
a little more sense.

00:16:36.710 --> 00:16:41.150
You start off with the nucleus
at 2.8 MeV above the neon

00:16:41.150 --> 00:16:42.980
nucleus' energy level.

00:16:42.980 --> 00:16:48.020
You need 1.022 MeV to create
the positron-electron pair,

00:16:48.020 --> 00:16:51.340
at which point you can emit the
positron with a certain energy.

00:16:51.340 --> 00:16:53.630
You're left in an excited
state, and the next thing

00:16:53.630 --> 00:16:58.130
we'll go over is gamma decay
or Isometric Transitions or IT.

00:16:58.130 --> 00:17:00.380
That's the next method of
decay we'll talk about.

00:17:00.380 --> 00:17:03.560
Or the nucleus can just
capture an electron,

00:17:03.560 --> 00:17:05.900
getting to that
same energy level

00:17:05.900 --> 00:17:08.579
and emitting the same gamma ray.

00:17:08.579 --> 00:17:12.210
So these are two competing
mechanisms of decay.

00:17:12.210 --> 00:17:13.839
And then you might
ask, well, when

00:17:13.839 --> 00:17:16.750
is one going to happen
and not the other?

00:17:16.750 --> 00:17:18.520
Well chances are,
the lower energy

00:17:18.520 --> 00:17:22.240
that transition is, the
more likely electron

00:17:22.240 --> 00:17:23.510
capture is going to happen.

00:17:23.510 --> 00:17:25.990
So when you look at
these energy diagrams,

00:17:25.990 --> 00:17:28.690
you can see that as the
transitions get bigger,

00:17:28.690 --> 00:17:33.300
the probability of positron
decay goes up and up and up.

00:17:33.300 --> 00:17:37.250
So you need 1.022 MeV to make
the positron an electron,

00:17:37.250 --> 00:17:42.030
but the probability of positron
decay very close to this

00:17:42.030 --> 00:17:43.310
is fairly low.

00:17:43.310 --> 00:17:46.620
Possible, but unlikely.

00:17:46.620 --> 00:17:49.620
Is everyone clear on these
two competing mechanisms?

00:17:49.620 --> 00:17:51.720
So one way of reducing
the number of protons

00:17:51.720 --> 00:17:55.578
is emit a positron, another
is gobble up an electron.

00:17:55.578 --> 00:17:57.620
In the end, they make the
same daughter products,

00:17:57.620 --> 00:17:59.690
but they go by
different mechanisms.

00:17:59.690 --> 00:18:02.490
And they give off
different bits of radiation

00:18:02.490 --> 00:18:06.075
which we can actually
sense and measure.

00:18:06.075 --> 00:18:07.970
Cool.

00:18:07.970 --> 00:18:10.690
So on to gamma decay or
isometric transition.

00:18:10.690 --> 00:18:12.850
These range from
the dead simple,

00:18:12.850 --> 00:18:16.120
like technetium-99
metastable giving off

00:18:16.120 --> 00:18:19.630
a characteristic 140 keV
gamma ray for technetium,

00:18:19.630 --> 00:18:21.130
that's the medical
imaging procedure

00:18:21.130 --> 00:18:22.345
we've talked a lot about.

00:18:22.345 --> 00:18:26.710
To the ridiculously
complex, like americium-241,

00:18:26.710 --> 00:18:29.980
which has a lot, a lot, a lot
of different nuclear energy

00:18:29.980 --> 00:18:34.030
states, all of which
release anywhere between 1

00:18:34.030 --> 00:18:36.500
and a lot of gamma rays.

00:18:36.500 --> 00:18:38.920
And this is what's referred
to as isometric transition.

00:18:38.920 --> 00:18:42.700
So we'll say gamma or
isometric transition

00:18:42.700 --> 00:18:46.810
is like the same thing, they're
just different words for it.

00:18:46.810 --> 00:18:47.950
These are called isomers.

00:18:47.950 --> 00:18:50.300
They've got the same number
of protons and neutrons,

00:18:50.300 --> 00:18:53.770
so it's the same nuclide,
but at an excited state.

00:18:53.770 --> 00:18:55.660
And we call it gamma
decay because we

00:18:55.660 --> 00:18:59.170
emit gamma rays or photons.

00:18:59.170 --> 00:19:01.810
I think this one is the
easiest one to understand,

00:19:01.810 --> 00:19:04.990
because the reaction
goes something like--

00:19:04.990 --> 00:19:06.490
let's say we have
a parent nucleus

00:19:06.490 --> 00:19:09.310
with Z protons and A neutrons.

00:19:12.380 --> 00:19:13.950
Nothing happens.

00:19:13.950 --> 00:19:16.640
It's about the easiest
nuclear reaction there is.

00:19:16.640 --> 00:19:19.820
Except you do give
off a gamma ray.

00:19:19.820 --> 00:19:22.280
And we'll usually put
a star or something

00:19:22.280 --> 00:19:24.680
to denote an excited state.

00:19:28.170 --> 00:19:31.640
So when you see a star
in the reading over there

00:19:31.640 --> 00:19:33.920
on a nuclide where
the charge would be,

00:19:33.920 --> 00:19:35.990
that's an excited energy
state that will likely

00:19:35.990 --> 00:19:41.220
decay by IT or gamma decay.

00:19:41.220 --> 00:19:44.490
There is also a
competing mechanism

00:19:44.490 --> 00:19:47.640
for isometric transition
or gamma decay,

00:19:47.640 --> 00:19:50.700
and that's what's called
internal conversion.

00:19:50.700 --> 00:19:52.293
In this case you
can kind of think

00:19:52.293 --> 00:19:54.460
of it-- this isn't the
correct physical explanation,

00:19:54.460 --> 00:19:57.150
but it's a perfectly
good mental model,

00:19:57.150 --> 00:19:58.980
that the gamma ray
would either just

00:19:58.980 --> 00:20:02.130
be emitted from the nucleus, at
which point you would see it,

00:20:02.130 --> 00:20:04.680
and the energy of the gamma
is the same as that Q,

00:20:04.680 --> 00:20:08.010
or it kind of hits an
electron on its way out,

00:20:08.010 --> 00:20:09.990
ejecting that electron.

00:20:09.990 --> 00:20:12.180
So instead of
finding a gamma ray,

00:20:12.180 --> 00:20:15.900
you may just get an electron
emitted at an energy very, very

00:20:15.900 --> 00:20:17.880
close to that gamma ray.

00:20:17.880 --> 00:20:20.850
The difference between the gamma
ray energy and the electron

00:20:20.850 --> 00:20:22.970
energy is its binding energy.

00:20:22.970 --> 00:20:25.530
Because if a gamma hits an
electron on the way out,

00:20:25.530 --> 00:20:29.010
it has to overcome the binding
energy of that electron,

00:20:29.010 --> 00:20:30.600
at which point the
rest of the energy

00:20:30.600 --> 00:20:33.460
is just its kinetic energy.

00:20:33.460 --> 00:20:36.970
So again, I don't think that's
the precise physical mechanism,

00:20:36.970 --> 00:20:39.880
but it's a perfectly good mental
model to remember what this is.

00:20:39.880 --> 00:20:42.370
A gamma can either
just get out on its own

00:20:42.370 --> 00:20:45.650
or it can hit an
electron on its way out.

00:20:45.650 --> 00:20:47.690
If you hit the electron
on your way out,

00:20:47.690 --> 00:20:50.030
just like in electron
capture, then

