00:54:24.150 --> 00:54:31.020
So we define the A, the
activity of a substance

00:54:31.020 --> 00:54:34.650
as pretty simple.

00:54:34.650 --> 00:54:38.300
It depends on the amount of
the substance that's there,

00:54:38.300 --> 00:54:41.190
and it depends on what's
called this decay constant.

00:54:41.190 --> 00:54:45.680
So this amount-- let's
just say like atoms.

00:54:45.680 --> 00:54:50.780
And this decay constant is
in units of 1 over second.

00:54:50.780 --> 00:54:53.570
An activity is in,
let's say, atoms

00:54:53.570 --> 00:54:58.950
destroyed or decays per second.

00:54:58.950 --> 00:55:02.720
That thing right there is called
the decay constant, lambda.

00:55:06.940 --> 00:55:09.520
And if we want to see, let's
say, how much of a substance

00:55:09.520 --> 00:55:12.670
is decaying at a certain
time or what's its activity

00:55:12.670 --> 00:55:16.460
and get a measure of how quickly
does it take to decay away,

00:55:16.460 --> 00:55:18.400
we can start by saying,
well this in effect

00:55:18.400 --> 00:55:21.790
is a destruction
rate of isotope N.

00:55:21.790 --> 00:55:25.150
So we can make the simplest
of differential equations

00:55:25.150 --> 00:55:30.100
and say, the amount of substance
N as a function of time

00:55:30.100 --> 00:55:36.470
is just minus its activity,
which equals minus lambda n.

00:55:36.470 --> 00:55:39.260
I hope I don't have to explain
how to solve this differential

00:55:39.260 --> 00:55:42.230
equation, so I'm going to go
through it pretty quickly.

00:55:42.230 --> 00:55:45.100
What's the method
you use for this

00:55:45.100 --> 00:55:46.870
to get n as a function of t?

00:55:49.582 --> 00:55:50.718
AUDIENCE: 3?

00:55:50.718 --> 00:55:51.510
MICHAEL SHORT: Yes.

00:55:51.510 --> 00:55:54.093
