00:55:55.260 --> 00:55:58.200
So we'll just separate
variables, divide each side

00:55:58.200 --> 00:56:01.100
by N, multiply side by dt.

00:56:01.100 --> 00:56:06.142
So we get dN over N
equals negative lambda dt.

00:56:06.142 --> 00:56:12.810
You can integrate both sides,
and we get the natural log of N

00:56:12.810 --> 00:56:17.678
equals minus lambda t plus
some integration constant.

00:56:17.678 --> 00:56:19.470
We're going to do a
little bit of trickery,

00:56:19.470 --> 00:56:24.220
and to make things in a nice
form that we can deal with,

00:56:24.220 --> 00:56:28.190
let's just call this log of N0.

00:56:28.190 --> 00:56:29.450
They're just numbers, right?

00:56:29.450 --> 00:56:33.180
We haven't defined what this
constant of integration is.

00:56:33.180 --> 00:56:35.930
Everyone cool with
us doing that?

00:56:35.930 --> 00:56:40.220
So then we can subtract
log of N0 from each side.

00:56:42.992 --> 00:56:52.910
And we get log N minus log
of N0 equals minus lambda t.

00:56:52.910 --> 00:57:01.370
So this is like saying log of N
over N0 equals minus lambda t.

00:57:01.370 --> 00:57:03.260
We'll take either the
power of both sides

00:57:03.260 --> 00:57:09.580
and we get N over and not
equals e to the minus lambda t.

00:57:09.580 --> 00:57:13.560
And right there you've got your
exponential decay equation.

00:57:13.560 --> 00:57:16.600
This is the easy part.

00:57:16.600 --> 00:57:19.720
And what this tells you is it
is a larger decay constant.

00:57:19.720 --> 00:57:21.370
Well let me ask you
a question, then.

00:57:21.370 --> 00:57:24.160
Would a larger decay
constant mean a faster

00:57:24.160 --> 00:57:26.358
or a slower decaying isotope?

00:57:30.940 --> 00:57:33.250
A larger decay
constant-- correct--

00:57:33.250 --> 00:57:36.220
means that you've got more
of these decays happening

00:57:36.220 --> 00:57:37.780
per second.

00:57:37.780 --> 00:57:43.050
So a larger lambda
means faster decay.

00:57:47.620 --> 00:57:49.330
And we also can
define a quantity

00:57:49.330 --> 00:58:02.420
called the half-life, which
means N at t 1/2 equals 1/2 N0.

00:58:02.420 --> 00:58:07.670
So for that, all you have to
do is plug in t 1/2 for t,

00:58:07.670 --> 00:58:12.980
and 1/2 N0 for N0, and you
actually get this relation

00:58:12.980 --> 00:58:20.180
where the half-life is just log
of 2 over lambda, better known

00:58:20.180 --> 00:58:22.700
as 0.693.

00:58:22.700 --> 00:58:25.690
But we'll just leave it
as log of 2 for exactness.

00:58:25.690 --> 00:58:28.610
And that's all there really
is for decay in half-life.

00:58:28.610 --> 00:58:30.500
So I'll pose another
question to you.

00:58:30.500 --> 00:58:35.420
Something with a
larger decay constant,

00:58:35.420 --> 00:58:38.680
will it have a larger
or a smaller half-life?

00:58:38.680 --> 00:58:39.540
AUDIENCE: Smaller?

00:58:39.540 --> 00:58:42.210
MICHAEL SHORT: Smaller, because
they're inversely related.

00:58:47.790 --> 00:58:49.440
So I'd say from this
quick derivation,

00:58:49.440 --> 00:58:51.990
these are the two
things to note.

00:58:51.990 --> 00:58:54.870
Is that something with a larger
decay constant decays faster

00:58:54.870 --> 00:58:57.210
and therefore has a
shorter half-life.

00:58:57.210 --> 00:59:00.000
So when we were separating
out our isotopes in nuclear

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:02.700
activation analysis into
what Mike called the shorts

00:59:02.700 --> 00:59:06.840
and the longs, he was separating
them by half-life to say that--

00:59:06.840 --> 00:59:08.670
let's say the same
amount of activation

00:59:08.670 --> 00:59:11.100
or the same amount
of creation, the ones

00:59:11.100 --> 00:59:15.420
with shorter half-lives will
be hotter, more radioactive,

00:59:15.420 --> 00:59:17.052
but for less time.

00:59:17.052 --> 00:59:18.510
And so what we're
going to be doing

00:59:18.510 --> 00:59:21.150
is what's called short
nuclear activation analysis

00:59:21.150 --> 00:59:23.610
because we don't want to
count for like days or weeks

00:59:23.610 --> 00:59:24.120
or months.

00:59:24.120 --> 00:59:24.760
Yep?

00:59:24.760 --> 00:59:27.010
AUDIENCE: So is half-life--
is the decay constant just

00:59:27.010 --> 00:59:29.915
a property of the given
substance, given element?

00:59:29.915 --> 00:59:31.290
MICHAEL SHORT:
The decay constant

00:59:31.290 --> 00:59:33.090
is a property of
the given isotope

00:59:33.090 --> 00:59:35.650
specific to that type of decay.

00:59:35.650 --> 00:59:40.740
So if we were to draw that
generalized radioactivity

00:59:40.740 --> 00:59:41.310
diagram--

00:59:41.310 --> 00:59:46.530
let's say we have potassium-40,
which can either go by beta

00:59:46.530 --> 00:59:48.990
decay to--

00:59:48.990 --> 00:59:51.060
what comes in beta--
what comes after--

00:59:51.060 --> 00:59:53.490
I think it's calcium-40.

00:59:53.490 --> 01:00:02.560
Or it can go by positron or
electron capture to argon-40.

01:00:02.560 --> 01:00:05.433
Each of these processes
has a different half-life.

01:00:05.433 --> 01:00:06.850
And then in that
chain-- remember,

01:00:06.850 --> 01:00:10.210
let's do the
americium-241, and I'm

01:00:10.210 --> 01:00:12.190
going to channel
my one-year-old son

01:00:12.190 --> 01:00:14.995
in drawing this decay diagram.

01:00:14.995 --> 01:00:21.720
It looks something like that
