01:00:57.560 --> 01:01:00.560
also known as an IT
transition, with a particularly

01:01:00.560 --> 01:01:01.832
long half-life.

01:01:04.487 --> 01:01:06.070
Everyone clear on
what all that means?

01:01:09.950 --> 01:01:10.773
Cool.

01:01:10.773 --> 01:01:12.190
Well, there'll be
some time for it

01:01:12.190 --> 01:01:17.560
to sink in because with
these definitions in hand,

01:01:17.560 --> 01:01:19.690
I want to pose a
problem to you guys.

01:01:19.690 --> 01:01:31.200
Let's say I start off with
some amount of an isotope N1.

01:01:31.200 --> 01:01:33.780
And it decays by
some mechanism--

01:01:33.780 --> 01:01:35.350
we don't care what--

01:01:35.350 --> 01:01:40.350
to isotope N2, and it
decays to some isotope N3

01:01:40.350 --> 01:01:45.480
with decay constants
lambda 1 and lambda 2.

01:01:45.480 --> 01:01:49.140
This is what we call
serial radioactive decay.

01:01:56.150 --> 01:01:58.010
How do we construct
a system of equations

01:01:58.010 --> 01:02:03.080
to tell us what is N1 as
a function of time, what

01:02:03.080 --> 01:02:06.710
is N2 as a function
of time, and what

01:02:06.710 --> 01:02:11.210
is N3 as a function of time?

01:02:11.210 --> 01:02:13.568
Where do we begin
in a general sense?

01:02:17.220 --> 01:02:19.980
OK, so let's start with N1.

01:02:19.980 --> 01:02:21.990
We kind of have an
expression for N1 already,

01:02:21.990 --> 01:02:24.840
but let's start out with
a differential equation.

01:02:24.840 --> 01:02:26.760
So the form of all
of these equations

01:02:26.760 --> 01:02:30.090
for everything serial
radioactive decay and burning

01:02:30.090 --> 01:02:33.300
isotopes in a reactor and
creating isotopes in a reactor

01:02:33.300 --> 01:02:36.060
is going to take
the following form.

01:02:36.060 --> 01:02:39.370
The general equation is simple.

01:02:39.370 --> 01:02:46.265
The change equals creation
minus destruction.

01:02:48.880 --> 01:02:54.070
Or the simple thing is
let's say the change is

01:02:54.070 --> 01:02:57.280
a source minus a sink.

01:02:57.280 --> 01:02:59.920
And we'll have to come up for
every one of these isotopes

01:02:59.920 --> 01:03:02.830
for a mathematical way to
describe what's the source

01:03:02.830 --> 01:03:04.330
and what's the sink.

01:03:04.330 --> 01:03:08.170
So if we want to
measure the change in N1

01:03:08.170 --> 01:03:12.410
as a function of time, what
are the sources of isotope N1?

01:03:12.410 --> 01:03:13.825
Yeah?

01:03:13.825 --> 01:03:15.200
AUDIENCE: Isn't
there no sources?

01:03:15.200 --> 01:03:17.690
MICHAEL SHORT: No sources.

01:03:17.690 --> 01:03:21.140
We're starting off with
some fixed quantity of N1.

01:03:21.140 --> 01:03:24.260
Let's just call it N1,0.

01:03:24.260 --> 01:03:27.320
But you're right, there's
no continuous source

01:03:27.320 --> 01:03:29.480
of isotope N1.

01:03:29.480 --> 01:03:33.296
What about its destruction?

01:03:33.296 --> 01:03:35.197
AUDIENCE: Decay to N2?

01:03:35.197 --> 01:03:36.030
MICHAEL SHORT: Yeah.

01:03:36.030 --> 01:03:36.840
Decay to N2.

01:03:36.840 --> 01:03:40.540
So we've got the equation
for that right there.

01:03:40.540 --> 01:03:44.410
it depends on the decay
constant of number 1

01:03:44.410 --> 01:03:46.347
and the amount of number 1.

01:03:46.347 --> 01:03:47.430
So what we're doing here--

01:03:47.430 --> 01:03:50.470
I love how this course is
timed with 18-03 because you're

01:03:50.470 --> 01:03:53.280
learning ordinary differential
equations in 18-03,

01:03:53.280 --> 01:03:55.780
and we're going to be solving
everyday ordinary differential

01:03:55.780 --> 01:03:57.722
equations for a fair
bit of this course.

01:03:57.722 --> 01:03:59.180
So it's one of
those rare times you

01:03:59.180 --> 01:04:01.780
